The home side were 54/1 - 187 runs behind - at tea on the third day.David Warner was 29 not out with Usman Khawaja on 24 in a stand of 54.Abbott had Joe Burns caught behind with a wide delivery down the leg side the fourth ball of the innings.Warner might also have become Abbott s second victim four balls before tea but Dean Elgar at third slip ducked under an edge that flew over his head.South Africa who resumed on 171/5 were dismissed 40 minutes after lunch for 326 in reply to Australia s first innings of 85.Quinton de Kock and Temba Bavuma who joined forces when South Africa were 132/5 added 144 before De Kock was bowled through the gate by Josh Hazlewood for 104.De Kock s effort was his second century in his 18 test innings and marked the fifth consecutive time he had gone past 50.Nine balls after lunch Bavuma was hurried into his stoke by Joe Mennie and spooned a catch to point for the debutant to claim his maiden test wicket.Vernon Philander s 32 off 28 balls with six fours was the best of the rest of South Africa s batting.